Importing my Libraries¶

In [33]:
from bs4 import BeautifulSoup
import requests
import pandas as pd 
import numpy as np
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt

Web Scrape Time¶

The table of interest comes from the comparison of races and their skills in one of my favorite games, The Elder Scrolls V: Skyrim.

In [2]:
url = 'https://elderscrolls.fandom.com/wiki/Races_(Skyrim)'

page = requests.get(url)

soup = BeautifulSoup(page.text, 'html')
In [3]:
print(soup)

            tier3Mapping: false,
        };
        const videoBridgeCountries = ["US","GB","CA","AU","DE","SG","MY","VN","ID","PH","TH","ES","FR","AR","MX","CO","PE","NZ","IN","DE","VN","FR","BR","ES","PL","CL"];
        const tier3VideoBridgeCountries = ["GB","BE","NL","DE","AU","MX","AR"];
        let hasVideoOnPage = null;

        function getCookieValue(cookieName) {
            const cookieSplit = ('; ' + document.cookie).split('; ' + cookieName + '=');
            return cookieSplit.length === 2 ? cookieSplit.pop().split(';').shift() : null;
        }

        function hasMaxedOutPlayerImpressionsInWiki() {
            const impressionsSoFar = Number(getCookieValue('playerImpressionsInWiki')) || 0;
            const allowedImpressions = Number(videoDetails.impressionsPerSession);

            return impressionsSoFar >= allowedImpressions;
        }

        function getCountryCode() {
            try {
                return JSON.parse(decodeURIComponent(getCookieValue('Geo'))).country.toLowerCase();
            } catch {
                return null;
            }
        }

        function isVideoBridgeAllowedForCountry() {
            const countryCode = getCountryCode();

            if (!countryCode) {
                return false;
            }

            // Check if the wiki is a tier3 wiki. This value comes back from the ArticleVideo service
            if (videoDetails && videoDetails.tier3Mapping) {
              // If the wiki is classified as a tier3 wiki, then check the country whitelist from the tier3VideoBridge whitelist.
              const allowedCountriesForTier3Wikis = tier3VideoBridgeCountries.map(function (allowedTier3CountryCode) {
                return allowedTier3CountryCode.toLowerCase();
              })

              return allowedCountriesForTier3Wikis.indexOf(countryCode) !== -1;
            } else {
              // If not a tier3 wiki, then check the country whitelist from the videoBridge whitelist
              const allowedCountries = videoBridgeCountries.map(function (allowedCountryCode) {
                return allowedCountryCode.toLowerCase();
              });

              return allowedCountries.indexOf(countryCode) !== -1;
            }
        }

        window.canPlayVideo = function () {
            if (hasVideoOnPage === null) {
                hasVideoOnPage =
                    videoDetails.mediaId && (videoDetails.isDedicatedForArticle || isVideoBridgeAllowedForCountry())
                    && !hasMaxedOutPlayerImpressionsInWiki();
            }

            return hasVideoOnPage;
        };

        if (!window.canPlayVideo()) {
            document.body.classList.add('no-featured-video');
        } else {
	        document.body.classList.add('has-featured-video');
        }
    })();
</script>

<div class="mw-parser-output"><figure class="thumb tright show-info-icon" style="width: 270px"> <a class="image" href="https://static.wikia.nocookie.net/elderscrolls/images/d/d2/Racesofskyrim.jpg/revision/latest?cb=20120214172445"><img alt="Racesofskyrim" class="thumbimage" data-image-key="Racesofskyrim.jpg" data-image-name="Racesofskyrim.jpg" data-relevant="1" decoding="async" height="166" loading="lazy" src="https://static.wikia.nocookie.net/elderscrolls/images/d/d2/Racesofskyrim.jpg/revision/latest/scale-to-width-down/270?cb=20120214172445" width="270"/></a> <figcaption class="thumbcaption"> <a class="info-icon" href="/wiki/File:Racesofskyrim.jpg"><svg><use xlink:href="#wds-icons-info-small"></use></svg></a> <p class="caption">Some of the playable races in <i>Skyrim</i>.</p> </figcaption> </figure>
<dl><dd><span><i>For other uses, see <a href="/wiki/Race" title="Race">Race</a>.</i></span></dd></dl>
<p>There are ten different playable <b>races</b> in <i><a href="/wiki/The_Elder_Scrolls_V:_Skyrim" title="The Elder Scrolls V: Skyrim">The Elder Scrolls V: Skyrim</a></i>. Each one possesses its own unique racial <a href="/wiki/Abilities_(Skyrim)" title="Abilities (Skyrim)">abilities</a> and <a href="/wiki/Powers_(Skyrim)" title="Powers (Skyrim)">powers</a>. Each race starts with +10 in one <a href="/wiki/Skills_(Skyrim)" title="Skills (Skyrim)">skill</a> and +5 in five other skills. However, this doesn't mean that a race is restricted to a certain play-style, as it is possible to develop any skill over time. Unlike other <i><a href="/wiki/The_Elder_Scrolls" title="The Elder Scrolls">The Elder Scrolls</a></i> games, <i>Skyrim</i> does not feature classes, so in character creation, the race is the only major gameplay choice that the player must make.
</p>

<h2><span class="mw-headline" id="Starting_skills_by_race">Starting skills by race</span></h2>
<p>The following table shows the starting skill statistics for each race. The higher the number (over the base level of 15) the better. Values of 20 indicate this is a favored skill of the race. Values of 25 indicate this is a primary skill of the race. Skills can be improved to a primary group.
</p><p>Every race has their own unique skill which they excel at and will start at level 25 with that particular skill. For example, <a href="/wiki/Bretons_(Skyrim)" title="Bretons (Skyrim)">Bretons</a> start at level 25 <a href="/wiki/Conjuration_(Skyrim)" title="Conjuration (Skyrim)">Conjuration</a> as they are naturally skilled at it.
</p>

<h2><span class="mw-headline" id="Starting_spells_by_race">Starting spells by race</span></h2>
<p>Every race begins with <a href="/wiki/Healing" title="Healing">Healing</a> and <a href="/wiki/Flames_(Skyrim)" title="Flames (Skyrim)">Flames</a>. Dunmer start with an additional <a href="/wiki/Sparks_(Skyrim)" title="Sparks (Skyrim)">Sparks</a>, whilst Altmer instead start with an additional <a href="/wiki/Fury_(Skyrim)" title="Fury (Skyrim)">Fury</a>, and Bretons instead start with an additional <a href="/wiki/Conjure_Familiar" title="Conjure Familiar">Conjure Familiar</a>.
</p>
<h2><span class="mw-headline" id="Survival_Mode"><a href="/wiki/Survival_Mode" title="Survival Mode">Survival Mode</a></span></h2>
<p><span style="box-shadow: 1px 1px 3px #000; border: 1px dotted White; font-size: smaller; font-weight:bold; color: #7994A3; vertical-align: 14%" title="Creation Club Content">Creation Club</span> The following are the additional racial effects in the <a href="/wiki/Creation_Club" title="Creation Club">Creation Club</a> of <i><a href="/wiki/The_Elder_Scrolls_V:_Skyrim_Anniversary_Edition" title="The Elder Scrolls V: Skyrim Anniversary Edition">The Elder Scrolls V: Skyrim Anniversary Edition</a></i>.
</p>
<ul><li>Argonian: <i>"Argonians become colder 25% faster in cold environments."</i>, <i>"Your Argonian blood allows you to eat raw meat without risk of disease."</i></li>
<li>Khajiit: <i>"Your Khajiit blood improves your resistance to cold environments by 15 points."</i>, <i>"Your Khajiit blood allows you to eat raw meat without risk of disease."</i></li>
<li>Nord: <i>"Your Nord blood improves your resistance to cold environments by 25 points."</i></li>
<li>Altmer: <i>"Your High Elf blood gives you 25% resistance to fatigue."</i></li>
<li>Bosmer: <i>"Your Bosmer blood gives you 25% resistance to fatigue."</i></li>
<li>Dunmer: <i>"Your Dunmer blood gives you 25% resistance to fatigue."</i></li>
<li>Orsimer: <i>"Your Orc blood gives you 15% resistance to hunger and fatigue, and increases your resistance to cold environments by 10 points."</i></li></ul>
<h2><span class="mw-headline" id="Stats_affected_by_character_size">Stats affected by character size</span></h2>
<figure class="thumb tright show-info-icon" style="width: 250px"> <a class="image" href="https://static.wikia.nocookie.net/elderscrolls/images/3/38/Getscalecommand.png/revision/latest?cb=20120123114048"><img alt="Getscalecommand" class="thumbimage lazyload" data-image-key="Getscalecommand.png" data-image-name="Getscalecommand.png" data-relevant="1" data-src="https://static.wikia.nocookie.net/elderscrolls/images/3/38/Getscalecommand.png/revision/latest/scale-to-width-down/250?cb=20120123114048" decoding="async" height="99" loading="lazy" src="data:image/gif;base64,R0lGODlhAQABAIABAAAAAP///yH5BAEAAAEALAAAAAABAAEAQAICTAEAOw%3D%3D" width="250"/></a> <noscript><a class="image" href="https://static.wikia.nocookie.net/elderscrolls/images/3/38/Getscalecommand.png/revision/latest?cb=20120123114048"><img alt="Getscalecommand" class="thumbimage" data-image-key="Getscalecommand.png" data-image-name="Getscalecommand.png" data-relevant="1" data-src="https://static.wikia.nocookie.net/elderscrolls/images/3/38/Getscalecommand.png/revision/latest/scale-to-width-down/250?cb=20120123114048" decoding="async" height="99" loading="lazy" src="https://static.wikia.nocookie.net/elderscrolls/images/3/38/Getscalecommand.png/revision/latest/scale-to-width-down/250?cb=20120123114048" width="250"/></a></noscript> <figcaption class="thumbcaption"> <a class="info-icon" href="/wiki/File:Getscalecommand.png"><svg><use xlink:href="#wds-icons-info-small"></use></svg></a> <p class="caption">Getscale command on a Male Nord. Returns 1.00.</p> </figcaption> </figure>
<p>Race specific scales can be found in the brackets when the <code>getscale</code> command is used on the player or a non-playable character. Non-bracket value is the default 1.00 console value and are unique for each specific race, for example, Altmer 1.00 value is different from Breton 1.00 value.
</p><p>At least walking/running speed and jump height is affected by the height value. The console command <code>player.setscale</code> can be used to change the height of the character. Because changing the player scale in the console increases and decreases melee damage accordingly, there is a misconception that taller races do more base melee damage.<sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-1"><a href="#cite_note-1">[1]</a></sup>
</p>

<h2><span class="mw-headline" id="Changes_from_previous_games">Changes from previous games</span></h2>
<p>Character creation has been dramatically changed in <i><a href="/wiki/The_Elder_Scrolls_V:_Skyrim" title="The Elder Scrolls V: Skyrim">The Elder Scrolls V: Skyrim</a></i>. Previous games had the player choose from a list of classes that would determine the starting skills for the player's character and in some cases, how the player's character would level. The player also had the option of creating a custom class, selecting each skill individually. This system had a very large impact on player effectiveness in the beginning of the game, though <i><a href="/wiki/The_Elder_Scrolls_IV:_Oblivion" title="The Elder Scrolls IV: Oblivion">Oblivion's</a></i> system was able to lessen that impact. A player could spend hours working out the most effective way to build a character.
</p><p>In <i>Skyrim</i>, however, that system has been removed, meaning that though the player will still select a race, the player no longer has to select a class. Skill set specialization is still possible in Skyrim, but instead of permanently selecting this during character creation, this is now done using the skill perks earned by leveling up (both skills and player level, as perks are earned by overall level while skill level is required to select any but the most basic perks). The <a class="mw-redirect" href="/wiki/Birthsign" title="Birthsign">birthsign</a> system has been replaced completely with <a href="/wiki/Standing_Stones" title="Standing Stones">Standing Stones</a>, which can be changed at any time by visiting and activating a new stone.
</p><p>The Luck attribute has also been removed and is therefore impossible to increase. Skills have been further reduced from a total of 21 to 18. There are no acrobatics/athletics or speed attributes so it is not possible to increase your jump height or your character's running speed through stats.
</p><p>If a player maxes out all skills, the character will reach level 81, meaning there are 80 (no perk can be chosen at level 1) possible perk points to choose from, out of over 250 possible places to spend them. Previously, this was the effective level cap for the player character, however this changed with <a href="/wiki/Patches_(Skyrim)" title="Patches (Skyrim)">Patch 1.9</a> and the introduction of <a href="/wiki/Skills_(Skyrim)#Legendary_Skills" title="Skills (Skyrim)">Legendary Skills</a>. Legendary skills allow the player to refund all the perk points from a single maxed out skill and set its level back to 15 (the game's starting point). Skills can be made legendary multiple times, allowing the player to level their character indefinitely.
</p><p>A typical player will not max out all skills to 100, and will instead reach only around level 50 or so. A character designed around 30 perk points is a reasonable build that can be reached in-game fairly quickly and is a great starting point for those who want to design the character before playing.
</p>
<h2><span class="mw-headline" id="Elders">Elders</span></h2>
<dl><dd><span><i>Main article: <a href="/wiki/Elder" title="Elder">Elder</a></i></span></dd></dl>
<p>In Skyrim, one of the races is called <b>Elder</b>. It cannot be chosen during character creation. It is solely composed of <a class="mw-redirect" href="/wiki/Human" title="Human">human</a> <a href="/wiki/Characters_(Skyrim)" title="Characters (Skyrim)">characters</a> that appear much older than most people. <a href="/wiki/Arngeir" title="Arngeir">Arngeir</a>, <a href="/wiki/Esbern_(Skyrim)" title="Esbern (Skyrim)">Esbern</a> and <a href="/wiki/Septimus_Signus" title="Septimus Signus">Septimus Signus</a> are some of the people who are part of the Elder race.<sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-2"><a href="#cite_note-2">[2]</a></sup>
</p>
<h2><span class="mw-headline" id="Snow_Elves">Snow Elves</span></h2>
<dl><dd><span><i>Main article: <a class="mw-redirect" href="/wiki/Snow_Elves" title="Snow Elves">Snow Elves</a></i></span></dd></dl>
<p>The Snow Elves are a race of <a href="/wiki/Mer" title="Mer">Mer</a> that cannot be chosen during character creation. During the events of <i><a href="/wiki/The_Elder_Scrolls_V:_Dawnguard" title="The Elder Scrolls V: Dawnguard">The Elder Scrolls V: Dawnguard</a></i>, two living Snow Elves are encountered, <a href="/wiki/Knight-Paladin_Gelebor" title="Knight-Paladin Gelebor">Knight-Paladin Gelebor</a> and his brother <a href="/wiki/Arch-Curate_Vyrthur" title="Arch-Curate Vyrthur">Arch-Curate Vyrthur</a>. They are, physically, very similar to High Elves, except for their white skin and hair.<sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-3"><a href="#cite_note-3">[3]</a></sup>
</p>

       <script data-name="featured-video-mapped-to-wiki">
        (function () {
        // we can't use mw.config here because it's too early so we need to pass this data in different way
        const videoDetails = {
            mediaId: "K21eFFRc",
            impressionsPerSession: 2,
            isDedicatedForArticle: false,
            tier3Mapping: false,
        };
        const videoBridgeCountries = ["US","GB","CA","AU","DE","SG","MY","VN","ID","PH","TH","ES","FR","AR","MX","CO","PE","NZ","IN","DE","VN","FR","BR","ES","PL","CL"];
        const tier3VideoBridgeCountries = ["GB","BE","NL","DE","AU","MX","AR"];
        let hasVideoOnPage = null;

        function getCookieValue(cookieName) {
            const cookieSplit = ('; ' + document.cookie).split('; ' + cookieName + '=');
            return cookieSplit.length === 2 ? cookieSplit.pop().split(';').shift() : null;
        }

        function hasMaxedOutPlayerImpressionsInWiki() {
            const impressionsSoFar = Number(getCookieValue('playerImpressionsInWiki')) || 0;
            const allowedImpressions = Number(videoDetails.impressionsPerSession);

            return impressionsSoFar >= allowedImpressions;
        }

        function getCountryCode() {
            try {
                return JSON.parse(decodeURIComponent(getCookieValue('Geo'))).country.toLowerCase();
            } catch {
                return null;
            }
        }

        function isVideoBridgeAllowedForCountry() {
            const countryCode = getCountryCode();

            if (!countryCode) {
                return false;
            }

            // Check if the wiki is a tier3 wiki. This value comes back from the ArticleVideo service
            if (videoDetails && videoDetails.tier3Mapping) {
              // If the wiki is classified as a tier3 wiki, then check the country whitelist from the tier3VideoBridge whitelist.
              const allowedCountriesForTier3Wikis = tier3VideoBridgeCountries.map(function (allowedTier3CountryCode) {
                return allowedTier3CountryCode.toLowerCase();
              })

              return allowedCountriesForTier3Wikis.indexOf(countryCode) !== -1;
            } else {
              // If not a tier3 wiki, then check the country whitelist from the videoBridge whitelist
              const allowedCountries = videoBridgeCountries.map(function (allowedCountryCode) {
                return allowedCountryCode.toLowerCase();
              });

              return allowedCountries.indexOf(countryCode) !== -1;
            }
        }

        window.canPlayVideo = function () {
            if (hasVideoOnPage === null) {
                hasVideoOnPage =
                    videoDetails.mediaId && (videoDetails.isDedicatedForArticle || isVideoBridgeAllowedForCountry())
                    && !hasMaxedOutPlayerImpressionsInWiki();
            }

            return hasVideoOnPage;
        };

        if (!window.canPlayVideo()) {
            document.body.classList.add('no-featured-video');
        } else {
	        document.body.classList.add('has-featured-video');
        }
    })();
       </script>

        <meta content="2023-12-13T10:16:57+00:00" itemprop="uploadDate"/>

        <noscript>

        <div class="mw-parser-output">
         <figure class="thumb tright show-info-icon" style="width: 270px">
          <a class="image" href="https://static.wikia.nocookie.net/elderscrolls/images/d/d2/Racesofskyrim.jpg/revision/latest?cb=20120214172445">
           <img alt="Racesofskyrim" class="thumbimage" data-image-key="Racesofskyrim.jpg" data-image-name="Racesofskyrim.jpg" data-relevant="1" decoding="async" height="166" loading="lazy" src="https://static.wikia.nocookie.net/elderscrolls/images/d/d2/Racesofskyrim.jpg/revision/latest/scale-to-width-down/270?cb=20120214172445" width="270"/>
          </a>
          <figcaption class="thumbcaption">
           <a class="info-icon" href="/wiki/File:Racesofskyrim.jpg">
            <svg>
             <use xlink:href="#wds-icons-info-small">
             </use>
            </svg>
           </a>
           <p class="caption">
            Some of the playable races in
            <i>
             Skyrim
            </i>
            .
           </p>
          </figcaption>
         </figure>
         <dl>
          <dd>
           <span>
            <i>
             For other uses, see
             <a href="/wiki/Race" title="Race">
              Race
             </a>
             .
            </i>
           </span>
          </dd>
         </dl>
         <p>
          There are ten different playable
          <b>
           races
          </b>
          in
          <i>
           <a href="/wiki/The_Elder_Scrolls_V:_Skyrim" title="The Elder Scrolls V: Skyrim">
            The Elder Scrolls V: Skyrim
           </a>
          </i>
          . Each one possesses its own unique racial
          <a href="/wiki/Abilities_(Skyrim)" title="Abilities (Skyrim)">
           abilities
          </a>
          and
          <a href="/wiki/Powers_(Skyrim)" title="Powers (Skyrim)">
           powers
          </a>
          . Each race starts with +10 in one
          <a href="/wiki/Skills_(Skyrim)" title="Skills (Skyrim)">
           skill
          </a>
          and +5 in five other skills. However, this doesn't mean that a race is restricted to a certain play-style, as it is possible to develop any skill over time. Unlike other
          <i>
           <a href="/wiki/The_Elder_Scrolls" title="The Elder Scrolls">
            The Elder Scrolls
           </a>
          </i>
          games,
          <i>
           Skyrim
          </i>
          does not feature classes, so in character creation, the race is the only major gameplay choice that the player must make.
         </p>

         <h2>
          <span class="mw-headline" id="Playable_races">
           Playable races
          </span>
         </h2>
         <p>
          <a href="/wiki/Tamriel" title="Tamriel">
           Tamriel
          </a>
          is the home of all the ten main races, each occupying a different portion of the continent.

         <h2>
          <span class="mw-headline" id="Starting_skills_by_race">
           Starting skills by race
          </span>
         </h2>
         <p>
          The following table shows the starting skill statistics for each race. The higher the number (over the base level of 15) the better. Values of 20 indicate this is a favored skill of the race. Values of 25 indicate this is a primary skill of the race. Skills can be improved to a primary group.
         </p>
         <p>
          Every race has their own unique skill which they excel at and will start at level 25 with that particular skill. For example,
          <a href="/wiki/Bretons_(Skyrim)" title="Bretons (Skyrim)">
           Bretons
          </a>
          start at level 25
          <a href="/wiki/Conjuration_(Skyrim)" title="Conjuration (Skyrim)">
           Conjuration
          </a>
          as they are naturally skilled at it.
         </p>

         <h2>
          <span class="mw-headline" id="Starting_spells_by_race">
           Starting spells by race
          </span>
         </h2>
         <p>
          Every race begins with
          <a href="/wiki/Healing" title="Healing">
           Healing
          </a>
          and
          <a href="/wiki/Flames_(Skyrim)" title="Flames (Skyrim)">
           Flames
          </a>
          . Dunmer start with an additional
          <a href="/wiki/Sparks_(Skyrim)" title="Sparks (Skyrim)">
           Sparks
          </a>
          , whilst Altmer instead start with an additional
          <a href="/wiki/Fury_(Skyrim)" title="Fury (Skyrim)">
           Fury
          </a>
          , and Bretons instead start with an additional
          <a href="/wiki/Conjure_Familiar" title="Conjure Familiar">
           Conjure Familiar
          </a>
          .
         </p>
         <h2>
          <span class="mw-headline" id="Survival_Mode">
           <a href="/wiki/Survival_Mode" title="Survival Mode">
            Survival Mode
           </a>
          </span>
         </h2>
         <p>
          <span style="box-shadow: 1px 1px 3px #000; border: 1px dotted White; font-size: smaller; font-weight:bold; color: #7994A3; vertical-align: 14%" title="Creation Club Content">
           Creation Club
          </span>
          The following are the additional racial effects in the
          <a href="/wiki/Creation_Club" title="Creation Club">
           Creation Club
          </a>
          of
          <i>
           <a href="/wiki/The_Elder_Scrolls_V:_Skyrim_Anniversary_Edition" title="The Elder Scrolls V: Skyrim Anniversary Edition">
            The Elder Scrolls V: Skyrim Anniversary Edition
           </a>
          </i>
          .
         </p>
         <ul>
          <li>
           Argonian:
           <i>
            "Argonians become colder 25% faster in cold environments."
           </i>
           ,
           <i>
            "Your Argonian blood allows you to eat raw meat without risk of disease."
           </i>
          </li>
          <li>
           Khajiit:
           <i>
            "Your Khajiit blood improves your resistance to cold environments by 15 points."
           </i>
           ,
           <i>
            "Your Khajiit blood allows you to eat raw meat without risk of disease."
           </i>
          </li>
          <li>
           Nord:
           <i>
            "Your Nord blood improves your resistance to cold environments by 25 points."
           </i>
          </li>
          <li>
           Altmer:
           <i>
            "Your High Elf blood gives you 25% resistance to fatigue."
           </i>
          </li>
          <li>
           Bosmer:
           <i>
            "Your Bosmer blood gives you 25% resistance to fatigue."
           </i>
          </li>
          <li>
           Dunmer:
           <i>
            "Your Dunmer blood gives you 25% resistance to fatigue."
           </i>
          </li>
          <li>
           Orsimer:
           <i>
            "Your Orc blood gives you 15% resistance to hunger and fatigue, and increases your resistance to cold environments by 10 points."
           </i>
          </li>
         </ul>
         <h2>
          <span class="mw-headline" id="Stats_affected_by_character_size">
           Stats affected by character size
          </span>
         </h2>
         <figure class="thumb tright show-info-icon" style="width: 250px">
          <a class="image" href="https://static.wikia.nocookie.net/elderscrolls/images/3/38/Getscalecommand.png/revision/latest?cb=20120123114048">
           <img alt="Getscalecommand" class="thumbimage lazyload" data-image-key="Getscalecommand.png" data-image-name="Getscalecommand.png" data-relevant="1" data-src="https://static.wikia.nocookie.net/elderscrolls/images/3/38/Getscalecommand.png/revision/latest/scale-to-width-down/250?cb=20120123114048" decoding="async" height="99" loading="lazy" src="data:image/gif;base64,R0lGODlhAQABAIABAAAAAP///yH5BAEAAAEALAAAAAABAAEAQAICTAEAOw%3D%3D" width="250"/>
          </a>
          <noscript>
           <a class="image" href="https://static.wikia.nocookie.net/elderscrolls/images/3/38/Getscalecommand.png/revision/latest?cb=20120123114048">
            <img alt="Getscalecommand" class="thumbimage" data-image-key="Getscalecommand.png" data-image-name="Getscalecommand.png" data-relevant="1" data-src="https://static.wikia.nocookie.net/elderscrolls/images/3/38/Getscalecommand.png/revision/latest/scale-to-width-down/250?cb=20120123114048" decoding="async" height="99" loading="lazy" src="https://static.wikia.nocookie.net/elderscrolls/images/3/38/Getscalecommand.png/revision/latest/scale-to-width-down/250?cb=20120123114048" width="250"/>
           </a>
          </noscript>
          <figcaption class="thumbcaption">
           <a class="info-icon" href="/wiki/File:Getscalecommand.png">
            <svg>
             <use xlink:href="#wds-icons-info-small">
             </use>
            </svg>
           </a>
           <p class="caption">
            Getscale command on a Male Nord. Returns 1.00.
           </p>
          </figcaption>
         </figure>
         <p>
          Race specific scales can be found in the brackets when the
          <code>
           getscale
          </code>
          command is used on the player or a non-playable character. Non-bracket value is the default 1.00 console value and are unique for each specific race, for example, Altmer 1.00 value is different from Breton 1.00 value.
         </p>
         <p>
          At least walking/running speed and jump height is affected by the height value. The console command
          <code>
           player.setscale
          </code>
          can be used to change the height of the character. Because changing the player scale in the console increases and decreases melee damage accordingly, there is a misconception that taller races do more base melee damage.
          <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-1">
           <a href="#cite_note-1">
            [1]
           </a>
          </sup>
         </p>

         <h2>
          <span class="mw-headline" id="Changes_from_previous_games">
           Changes from previous games
          </span>
         </h2>
         <p>
          Character creation has been dramatically changed in
          <i>
           <a href="/wiki/The_Elder_Scrolls_V:_Skyrim" title="The Elder Scrolls V: Skyrim">
            The Elder Scrolls V: Skyrim
           </a>
          </i>
          . Previous games had the player choose from a list of classes that would determine the starting skills for the player's character and in some cases, how the player's character would level. The player also had the option of creating a custom class, selecting each skill individually. This system had a very large impact on player effectiveness in the beginning of the game, though
          <i>
           <a href="/wiki/The_Elder_Scrolls_IV:_Oblivion" title="The Elder Scrolls IV: Oblivion">
            Oblivion's
           </a>
          </i>
          system was able to lessen that impact. A player could spend hours working out the most effective way to build a character.
         </p>
         <p>
          In
          <i>
           Skyrim
          </i>
          , however, that system has been removed, meaning that though the player will still select a race, the player no longer has to select a class. Skill set specialization is still possible in Skyrim, but instead of permanently selecting this during character creation, this is now done using the skill perks earned by leveling up (both skills and player level, as perks are earned by overall level while skill level is required to select any but the most basic perks). The
          <a class="mw-redirect" href="/wiki/Birthsign" title="Birthsign">
           birthsign
          </a>
          system has been replaced completely with
          <a href="/wiki/Standing_Stones" title="Standing Stones">
           Standing Stones
          </a>
          , which can be changed at any time by visiting and activating a new stone.
         </p>
         <p>
          The Luck attribute has also been removed and is therefore impossible to increase. Skills have been further reduced from a total of 21 to 18. There are no acrobatics/athletics or speed attributes so it is not possible to increase your jump height or your character's running speed through stats.
         </p>
         <p>
          If a player maxes out all skills, the character will reach level 81, meaning there are 80 (no perk can be chosen at level 1) possible perk points to choose from, out of over 250 possible places to spend them. Previously, this was the effective level cap for the player character, however this changed with
          <a href="/wiki/Patches_(Skyrim)" title="Patches (Skyrim)">
           Patch 1.9
          </a>
          and the introduction of
          <a href="/wiki/Skills_(Skyrim)#Legendary_Skills" title="Skills (Skyrim)">
           Legendary Skills
          </a>
          . Legendary skills allow the player to refund all the perk points from a single maxed out skill and set its level back to 15 (the game's starting point). Skills can be made legendary multiple times, allowing the player to level their character indefinitely.
         </p>
         <p>
          A typical player will not max out all skills to 100, and will instead reach only around level 50 or so. A character designed around 30 perk points is a reasonable build that can be reached in-game fairly quickly and is a great starting point for those who want to design the character before playing.
         </p>
         <h2>
          <span class="mw-headline" id="Elders">
           Elders
          </span>
         </h2>
         <dl>
          <dd>
           <span>
            <i>
             Main article:
             <a href="/wiki/Elder" title="Elder">
              Elder
             </a>
            </i>
           </span>
          </dd>
         </dl>
         <p>
          In Skyrim, one of the races is called
          <b>
           Elder
          </b>
          . It cannot be chosen during character creation. It is solely composed of
          <a class="mw-redirect" href="/wiki/Human" title="Human">
           human
          </a>
          <a href="/wiki/Characters_(Skyrim)" title="Characters (Skyrim)">
           characters
          </a>
          that appear much older than most people.
          <a href="/wiki/Arngeir" title="Arngeir">
           Arngeir
          </a>
          ,
          <a href="/wiki/Esbern_(Skyrim)" title="Esbern (Skyrim)">
           Esbern
          </a>
          and
          <a href="/wiki/Septimus_Signus" title="Septimus Signus">
           Septimus Signus
          </a>
          are some of the people who are part of the Elder race.
          <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-2">
           <a href="#cite_note-2">
            [2]
           </a>
          </sup>
         </p>
         <h2>
          <span class="mw-headline" id="Snow_Elves">
           Snow Elves
          </span>
         </h2>
         <dl>
          <dd>
           <span>
            <i>
             Main article:
             <a class="mw-redirect" href="/wiki/Snow_Elves" title="Snow Elves">
              Snow Elves
             </a>
            </i>
           </span>
          </dd>
         </dl>
         <p>
          The Snow Elves are a race of
          <a href="/wiki/Mer" title="Mer">
           Mer
          </a>
          that cannot be chosen during character creation. During the events of
          <i>
           <a href="/wiki/The_Elder_Scrolls_V:_Dawnguard" title="The Elder Scrolls V: Dawnguard">
            The Elder Scrolls V: Dawnguard
           </a>
          </i>
          , two living Snow Elves are encountered,
          <a href="/wiki/Knight-Paladin_Gelebor" title="Knight-Paladin Gelebor">
           Knight-Paladin Gelebor
          </a>
          and his brother
          <a href="/wiki/Arch-Curate_Vyrthur" title="Arch-Curate Vyrthur">
           Arch-Curate Vyrthur
          </a>
          . They are, physically, very similar to High Elves, except for their white skin and hair.
          <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-3">
           <a href="#cite_note-3">
            [3]
           </a>
          </sup>
         </p>

Working with a Dataframe¶

I successfully retrieved the titles but I still need to make some minor tweaks because all the titles were thrown into one long horizontal header. What I want is the races to go across and the skills to down the table.

In [19]:
df = pd.DataFrame(columns = race_table_titles)

df

Races Skills Altmer Argonian Bosmer Breton Dunmer Imperial Khajiit Nord Orsimer ... Lockpicking Pickpocket Speech Alchemy Illusion Conjuration Destruction Restoration Alteration Enchanting

0 rows 29 columns

Visualization Time¶

I felt that a bar plot would work well for this type of data.

In [55]:
plt.figure(figsize=(15, 8))
sns.barplot(data=df,
            x="Skills",
            y="Altmer")
plt.title('Altmer Starting Stats')
plt.xlabel('Skills')
# Rotate x-axis labels
plt.xticks(rotation=25)
plt.ylabel('Points')
plt.show()

I successfully created a visualization for the Altmer race, but it would be a pain to copy and paste this code several times. I can just use a for loop to make my life easier!

In [56]:
races = ['Altmer','Argonian','Bosmer','Breton','Dunmer','Imperial','Khajiit','Nord','Orsimer','Redguard']

for race in races:
    
    plt.figure(figsize=(15, 4))
    sns.barplot(data=df,
            x='Skills',
            y=race)
    plt.title(f'{race} Starting Stats')
    plt.xlabel('Skills')
    # Rotate x-axis labels
    plt.xticks(rotation=25)
    plt.ylabel('Points')
    plt.show()

Even though there are already several resources to tell you the different stats of each race in Skyrim, I thought it would be fun to start my web scraping journey with something simple and a topic that I love! Personally, I enjoy the easy to look at charts. It allows me to quickly assess what race to start as if I want a specific build. For example, if I wanted a pure mage build, based on stats alone, I would need higher points in the magic skills. A quick glance through all of them shows me that Altmer is the way to go (my personal favorite).

Hope You Enjoyed!¶
